      <hedline>
        <hl1>Miller on Monday</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joseph Carducci letter welcomes Dennis Miller's good-natured barbs as Monday Night Football announcer/</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Like many people, I had reservations about the comedian Dennis Miller working in the broadcast booth of ''Monday Night Football.'' After all, football has gone from being a spectator sport to a national obsession, and we expect its analysis to be presented in the form of a military science.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Like many people, I had reservations about the comedian Dennis Miller working in the broadcast booth of ''Monday Night Football.'' After all, football has gone from being a spectator sport to a national obsession, and we expect its analysis to be presented in the form of a military science.</p>
        <p>Miller's good-natured barbs were a welcome relief to this mock seriousness, however, and his presence reminded us that any football game is still, after all, only a game.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH CARDUCCI  Pittsburgh</p>
      </block>
